Making a new repo
log in to GitHub.com and create a new, empty repository (name it kimballH). 
Do not initialize it with a README, license, or gitignore if you want to keep the process simple.
Initialize and Push Your Folder
Open your terminal and run these commands to connect your local folder to GitHub
.1.Navigate to your folder:Terminal.Change directory into your kimballH folder:
	Bash cd /path/to/your/kimballH
2.Initialize Git:Setup.Turn the folder into a Git repository:
	Bash git init -b main
3.Add files to staging:Tracking.Stage all files in the folder to be committed:
	Bash git add .
4.Commit changes:Snapshot.Create your initial commit:Bashgit commit -m "Initial commit of KimballH photos and data"
5.Connect to GitHub:Remote.Add the remote URL (replace YOUR_USERNAME with your GitHub handle):Bashgit remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/kimballH.git
6.Push to GitHub:Sync.Upload your files to the main branch:Bashgit push -u origin main
Important: Large File Handling (Git LFS)Since you are working with photos (HEIF/JPEG), do not upload them to GitHub if the folder is large (over 100MB total). GitHub will reject files larger than 100MB and will struggle with large image libraries.If you intend to store these photos in this repository, you must use Git LFS (Large File Storage):Install LFS: git lfs installTrack images: Run this inside the kimballH folder:Bashgit lfs track "*.jpg" "*.heic" "*.heif" "*.tif"
